<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-255-551  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 255 551.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  Jan 1989 v62 n1 p89(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>An ample 7% hike is in the cards. (forecast sales of industrialelectronic equipment)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Electronics magazine expects the US industrial electronicequipment market to grow seven percent and reach sales of $6.3billion in 1989, down two percent from 1988.andP;  Sales to the processindustries and the automotive industry should continue to grow,boosted by the trend toward automation, but the recent rash ofmergers and acquisitions could have a negative effect on themarket.andP;  Sales of process control equipment are predicted toincrease by seven percent and hit $3.8 billion, led byinstrumentation sales of $2.77 billion.andP;  Vision systems areexpected to reach sales of $200 million quickly, followed byinspection system sales of $375 million.andP;  The sale of robotsystems will probably grow by four percent for a total revenue of$431 million and should maintain that growth for several years.andO;Other specific sales forecasts for industrial equipment are given.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic IndustryIndustry AnalysisGrowthForecastingSales.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablegraph.andO;Caption:   Industrial equipment sales 1987-1989. (table)Process control equipment sales 1987-1989 and market share for1989. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>